\details{
Antonym pairs are item pairs whose whole-sample inter-item correlation is below
\code{-critical_r}. Pairing uses raw responses (no reverse-scoring, which would collapse
those negative correlations toward zero); the score is the single correlation across
all qualifying pairs' stacked values. Supply \code{critical_r} as a positive magnitude in
\verb{(0, 1)} applied to the negative tail, matching \code{\link[=cier_psychsyn]{cier_psychsyn()}} and the pairing
diagnostics (\code{\link[=cier_synonym_pairs]{cier_synonym_pairs()}}, \code{\link[=cier_psychsyn_critval]{cier_psychsyn_critval()}} with \code{antonym = TRUE})
so one threshold means the same pair strength for synonyms and antonyms; a negative
value is an input error.

\code{critical_r} is a property of the inventory: if no two items oppose each other
strongly enough, no pairs qualify, every value is \code{NA}, and the index abstains with a
warning -- lower \code{critical_r}, or use a scale pairing forward and reverse items
(\code{\link[=cier_synonym_pairs]{cier_synonym_pairs()}} with \code{antonym = TRUE} lists qualifying pairs). A respondent
with fewer than three complete pairs, or zero-variance pair values (a straightliner),
also has \code{NA} \code{value} and \code{flagged}.

The default cutoff flags the lowest-opposition respondents at the \code{1 - fpr} quantile
(95th percentile). This ranking flags at least \code{fpr} of respondents, not a calibrated
false-positive rate; adjust with \code{fpr}, or pass an absolute \code{cutoff} in \verb{[-1, 1]}
(mutually exclusive).
}
\section{What this catches}{

Random and partial / changepoint responding. It misses pure straightlining and
midpoint locking (a constant row abstains); pair it with \code{\link[=cier_longstring]{cier_longstring()}} and
\code{\link[=cier_irv]{cier_irv()}}. It also needs genuine antonym pairs to exist -- usually forward/reverse
item pairs.
}

\section{Pairing reference on contaminated samples}{

When much of the sample responds carelessly the antonym correlations shrink toward
zero and no pair clears \code{-critical_r}, so the index abstains exactly when carelessness
is highest. \code{reference} estimates the pairs on a clean source -- a screened subset of
the analysis rows, or a separate clean sample -- while every respondent is still
scored on the full sample. Such workflows usually supply a clean \code{reference} and relax
the strict default \code{critical_r} (e.g. to \code{0.40}). \code{reference = NULL} (default) uses
whole-sample self-pairing.
}

